headline: Super Micro drops after weak Q1 results, but guidance lifts long-term hopes
summary: Investing.com -- Shares of Super Micro Computer Inc (NASDAQ:SMCI) declined more than 6% in after-hours trading Tuesday after the company reported fiscal Q1 results that fell short of expectations, despite boosting revenue guidance for the current quarter and full year. The company missed analysts’ estimates on both earnings and top-line performance, raising questions about near-term demand execution even as longer-term AI infrastructure bets remain in focus.

headline: Super Micro (NASDAQ:SMCI) Misses Q3 Revenue Estimates, Stock Drops
summary: Server solutions provider Super Micro (NASDAQ:SMCI) missed Wall Street’s revenue expectations in Q3 CY2025, with sales falling 15.5% year on year to $5.02 billion. On the other hand, next quarter’s outlook exceeded expectations with revenue guided to $10.5 billion at the midpoint, or 31.5% above analysts’ estimates. Its non-GAAP profit of $0.35 per share was 10.1% below analysts’ consensus estimates.

headline: Super Micro misses quarterly estimates on delivery delays
summary: (Reuters) -Super Micro Computer missed Wall Street estimates for quarterly profit and revenue on Tuesday, hit by a shift in delivery schedules for large artificial intelligence deals, sending the server maker's shares down more than 8% in extended trading.  Nearly $1.5 billion in revenue shifted from the September quarter to the December quarter due to last-minute configuration upgrades by a high-volume customer, CEO Charles Liang said on a post-earnings call with analysts.  "These shifts were largely caused by the complexity of these new graphics processing unit (GPU) racks, which require intricate integration, testing, and validation — making them more time-consuming to source and build," Liang added.

"These shifts were largely caused by the complexity of these new graphics processing unit (GPU) racks, which require intricate integration, testing, and validation — making them more time-consuming to source and build," Liang added.
